Chapter 1: What is Hashing?

Imagine you're a teacher.

A student asks

"How many times did Rahul come to class?"

Method 1 (Without hashing)

You check the attendance register.

Rahul
Ankit
Rahul
Ishan
Rahul
Aryan

You scan every page.

Time = O(n)

Method 2 (With hashing)

You already have a notebook like

Rahul -> 3

Ankit ->1

Ishan ->1

Aryan ->1

Student asks again

Rahul?

You immediately answer

3

Time = O(1)

This notebook is called a Hash Table.

Hashing simply means

Store data so you can find it very quickly.

Real Life Example

Your phone contacts.

Suppose you save

Rahul
Ishan
Aryan

When you type

Ish

It instantly finds

Ishan

Your phone is using hashing internally.

Think of Hashing Like This

Instead of searching

1
2
3
4
5
6
7

every time,

you directly know

4 is stored here.

No searching.

Direct lookup.

Chapter 2: STL Containers Used for Hashing

There are three important ones.

1) unordered_map

Stores

Key -> Value

Example

unordered_map<string,int> mp;

mp["Rahul"]=90;
mp["Ishan"]=95;
mp["Aryan"]=88;

Now

cout<<mp["Ishan"];

prints

95
2) unordered_set

Stores only unique values.

unordered_set<int> s;

s.insert(5);
s.insert(10);
s.insert(5);

Result

5
10

Duplicate removed automatically.

Useful for checking

"Have I seen this before?"

3) map

Works like unordered_map but keeps keys sorted.

1
2
3
4
5

instead of random order.

Searching

O(log n)

instead of average

O(1)

In interviews,

Most of the time

unordered_map

is preferred.

Chapter 3: Why O(1)?

Suppose

1000000 numbers

Without hashing

Finding

999999

means searching almost everything.

O(n)

With hashing

999999

directly jumps to its location.

Average

O(1)
Chapter 4: Frequency Counting

This is THE most common hashing application.

Suppose

nums

1 2 2 3 1 1 5

We want

1 occurs 3 times

2 occurs 2 times

3 occurs 1 time

5 occurs 1 time

How?

unordered_map<int,int> freq;

for(int x:nums)
{
    freq[x]++;
}

After loop

1 ->3

2 ->2

3 ->1

5 ->1

Done.

Visualization

Start

{}

Read

1
1->1

Read

2
1->1

2->1

Read

2
1->1

2->2

Read

1
1->2

2->2

Eventually

1->3

2->2

3->1

5->1
Chapter 5: Presence Checking

Question

Does array contain 7?

Without hashing

for(...)

O(n)

With hashing

unordered_set<int> st;

for(int x:nums)
    st.insert(x);

if(st.count(7))

Done.

Average

O(1)
